00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:25.090 --> 00:00:26.390
&gt;&gt; Robert Newlen: Good
morning, everyone,

00:00:26.390 --> 00:00:28.390
and welcome to the
Library of Congress.

00:00:28.390 --> 00:00:31.630
It's good to see so
many people here today.

00:00:31.630 --> 00:00:34.100
Our program today is a continuation

00:00:34.100 --> 00:00:36.960
of our Congressional
conversation series

00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:41.400 position:56%
in which the library invites current
and former members of Congress

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:44.900
to discuss their careers
in public service.

00:00:44.900 --> 00:00:47.010
It's a real honor and
privilege for me

00:00:47.010 --> 00:00:50.170
to welcome Representative
Jackie Speier today

00:00:50.170 --> 00:00:52.670
and to welcome her to the Library.

00:00:52.670 --> 00:00:55.570
Representative Speier has
had a distinguished career

00:00:55.570 --> 00:00:59.660
in public service, from her
time as a Congressional staffer,

00:00:59.660 --> 00:01:05.780
as a state legislator, and her
current role as member of Congress.

00:01:05.780 --> 00:01:09.740
She represents the 14th District
of California in the House.

00:01:09.740 --> 00:01:11.670
Everyone knows where that is --

00:01:11.670 --> 00:01:15.300
San Francisco area,
absolutely beautiful.

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:18.410
She is the ranking member on the
House Armed Services Subcommittee

00:01:18.410 --> 00:01:21.560
on Oversight and Investigations
and also serves

00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:26.090
on the House Permanent Select
Committee on Intelligence.

00:01:26.090 --> 00:01:30.180
Among the issues that she has
focused on: Ending sexual assault

00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:37.830
in the military; gender pay equity;
consumer protection; cybersecurity;

00:01:37.830 --> 00:01:41.510
and student loan affordability.

00:01:41.510 --> 00:01:44.610
Representative Speier has
a fascinating personal

00:01:44.610 --> 00:01:47.610
and professional story
to share with us.

00:01:47.610 --> 00:01:50.600
She's overcome adversity
numerous times in her life

00:01:50.600 --> 00:01:54.100
and channeled those
experiences into an impressive

00:01:54.100 --> 00:01:57.710
and distinguished career
in government service.

00:01:57.710 --> 00:02:00.920
Our conversation today will
be led by Colleen Shogan,

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:02.500
the Deputy Director of our National

00:02:02.500 --> 00:02:06.350
and International Outreach
Service Unit here at the Library.

00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:08.990
Colleen is a political
scientist by training

00:02:08.990 --> 00:02:12.420
and a self-described
lover of Congress.

00:02:12.420 --> 00:02:18.800
I also want to commend to
you this wonderful book,

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:22.010
which Represent Speier co-authored.

00:02:22.010 --> 00:02:24.660
I think you'll all
appreciate this title:

00:02:24.660 --> 00:02:27.960
<i>This is Not the Life I Ordered</i>.

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:30.520
This is a great book to
keep right at your desk

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:32.720
when you're having
those bad moments.

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:35.360
I've already consulted
it several times.

00:02:35.360 --> 00:02:40.510
So it's my pleasure to
welcome Representative Speier.

00:02:40.510 --> 00:02:48.430
[ Applause ]

00:02:48.430 --> 00:02:49.730
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Terrific.

00:02:49.730 --> 00:02:51.350
Good morning and welcome
to the Library of Congress.

00:02:51.350 --> 00:02:54.580
I think we're going to have a great
conversation here this morning.

00:02:54.580 --> 00:02:57.750
At the conclusion of our
conversation back and forth,

00:02:57.750 --> 00:03:02.050
Representative Speier is happy to
take questions from the audience.

00:03:02.050 --> 00:03:03.740
But I'm going to kick us off.

00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:07.430
So you were interested in politics
at a young age, but you didn't grow

00:03:07.430 --> 00:03:10.180
up in a particularly
political family.

00:03:10.180 --> 00:03:14.550
For your confirmation you
chose the name Jacqueline

00:03:14.550 --> 00:03:16.500
because of Jackie Kennedy.

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:20.270
So can you tell us at a younger
age what got you interested

00:03:20.270 --> 00:03:24.000
in politics and public service?

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.560
&gt;&gt; Rep. Jackie Speier: I came
from a very blue collar family --

00:03:28.560 --> 00:03:30.810 position:56%
first in my family to go to college.

00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:33.800
Not politically active,
as you pointed out.

00:03:33.800 --> 00:03:40.020
I guess I was 10, 11, 12 years
old during the Camelot Era

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:42.950
of the Kennedy Administration.

00:03:42.950 --> 00:03:47.190
And I think everyone in the country
was uplifted by this young couple

00:03:47.190 --> 00:03:55.140 position:56%
who had taken Washington by storm
and the sense of hope and aspiration

00:03:55.140 --> 00:04:01.610
that was, I think, so
vividly there and palpable.

00:04:01.610 --> 00:04:05.590
And so I guess that's
what first drew me in.

00:04:05.590 --> 00:04:09.450
And then I did take the name
Jacqueline at the confirmation.

00:04:09.450 --> 00:04:13.380
I hated the name Karen because
my mother would always yell Karen

00:04:13.380 --> 00:04:17.230
and it would just drive me nuts.

00:04:17.230 --> 00:04:20.000
So I took Jacqueline
as a confirmation name.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.180
And then I when from a
public elementary school

00:04:23.180 --> 00:04:25.730
to a Catholic girl's
high school by choice,

00:04:25.730 --> 00:04:28.330
which was another interesting
point in my life.

00:04:28.330 --> 00:04:31.790
And so I was meeting a
whole new group of students.

00:04:31.790 --> 00:04:34.970
And so I just decided that I
was going to take my nickname

00:04:34.970 --> 00:04:37.350
at that point and make it Jackie.

00:04:37.350 --> 00:04:39.130
That's how that involved.

00:04:39.130 --> 00:04:42.950
In terms of politics I think I
just remember reading the local

00:04:42.950 --> 00:04:49.080
newspapers and I was drawn to
this local mayor, who was young --

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:51.250
Leo Ryan, mayor of
South San Francisco --

00:04:51.250 --> 00:04:55.120
who then ran for the state
assembly and got elected.

00:04:55.120 --> 00:04:59.540
And there's a plan for all us.

00:04:59.540 --> 00:05:01.100
And we don't always know the plan.

00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:05.630
But I'm 16 years of age; my parents
get a solicitation in the mail

00:05:05.630 --> 00:05:09.010
for Assemblyman Ryan's reelection.

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:13.760
I take it, fill it out, say I have
no money but I would volunteer.

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:16.890
And then Saturday morning my
job was to vacuum the house.

00:05:16.890 --> 00:05:20.110
And so I'm vacuuming the
house and the phone rings.

00:05:20.110 --> 00:05:21.440
The vacuum cleaner's still going.

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:23.910
I hear this voice on
the other end saying,

00:05:23.910 --> 00:05:26.000
"Would you come to be interviewed?"

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.270
And it was Leo Ryan.

00:05:29.270 --> 00:05:34.700
And he was having a campaign
meeting at his home in Millbrea.

00:05:34.700 --> 00:05:37.670
And I went up and was interviewed.

00:05:37.670 --> 00:05:39.600
And they were actually
interviewing young women

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:42.120
to be what they called
that year Ryan Girls.

00:05:42.120 --> 00:05:47.200
And there's a picture of me
in my office as a Ryan Girl.

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:49.560
And it was at the height
of the Beatles.

00:05:49.560 --> 00:05:55.240
So we all had boots, black
tights, little miniskirts,

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:58.470
a little kind of British hat on.

00:05:58.470 --> 00:06:04.430
And we went around the
communities just campaigning

00:06:04.430 --> 00:06:06.120
for then Assemblyman Leo Ryan.

00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:07.980
And that's how it all started.

00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:11.070 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: And you continued
to work for Leo Ryan when you went

00:06:11.070 --> 00:06:16.150 position:56%
to UC Davis and as you were going
to law school as well in California.

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:19.580
Can you tell us a little
bit about Leo Ryan?

00:06:19.580 --> 00:06:24.720
He had a unique view of his
job as a representative.

00:06:24.720 --> 00:06:27.570
He became your political mentor.

00:06:27.570 --> 00:06:31.220
So can you talk to us a little
bit about what Leo Ryan was like?

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:33.510
&gt;&gt; Rep. Jackie Speier: So he was --

00:06:33.510 --> 00:06:36.470
I always said he ate
bureaucrats for lunch.

00:06:36.470 --> 00:06:44.850
He had this inquisitive sense
of wanting to know more.

00:06:44.850 --> 00:06:48.280
And he was, you know, a teacher by
profession, so he taught history

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:50.250
and government and English.

00:06:50.250 --> 00:06:53.820
And he, you know, told me that
I didn't know how to write

00:06:53.820 --> 00:06:56.990
when he read my paper in college.

00:06:56.990 --> 00:07:00.530
And it was actually a critical
analysis of his operation.

00:07:00.530 --> 00:07:05.250
And I had gotten an A-minus on it.

00:07:05.250 --> 00:07:08.610
He crossed the A-minus out and put
C-minus and said I didn't know how

00:07:08.610 --> 00:07:11.730
to write and he was
going to teach me.

00:07:11.730 --> 00:07:16.120
But he also had this sense
of being experiential.

00:07:16.120 --> 00:07:21.690
Because he had a healthy
sense of skepticism,

00:07:21.690 --> 00:07:23.250
he wanted to do things himself.

00:07:23.250 --> 00:07:28.580
So after the riots in Los
Angeles, he went down there

00:07:28.580 --> 00:07:31.190
and taught school there for a week.

00:07:31.190 --> 00:07:34.140
He wanted to look at the criminal
justice system in California,

00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:39.920
so he put himself in Folsom
Prison for a week to evaluate that

00:07:39.920 --> 00:07:44.370
and actually wrote a play
based on his experience there

00:07:44.370 --> 00:07:45.740
that never got published.

00:07:45.740 --> 00:07:53.030
But so he had by his very core this
sense of wanting to see firsthand.

00:07:53.030 --> 00:07:56.880
There was nothing like being
there as opposed to listening

00:07:56.880 --> 00:08:03.250
to some advisor tell you
about a particular issue.

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:05.530
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: When you were
working for Congressman Ryan

00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:08.380
as a senior legal counsel
after you had graduated,

00:08:08.380 --> 00:08:09.800
after you had earned
your law degree,

00:08:09.800 --> 00:08:16.500
in 1978 Congressman Ryan decided
that he would lead a delegation

00:08:16.500 --> 00:08:21.950
to Guyana to visit the
Peoples Temple commune

00:08:21.950 --> 00:08:25.360
that Jim Jones had
assembled in Guyana.

00:08:25.360 --> 00:08:29.430
And you were a senior part of his
Congressional staff at that time.

00:08:29.430 --> 00:08:33.850
Can you tell us about the
decision that Congressman Ryan made

00:08:33.850 --> 00:08:35.610
to actually lead this delegation?

00:08:35.610 --> 00:08:40.630
Why did he decide to go to
visit Jonestown and knowing

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:44.080
that it was a dangerous --
could be a dangerous trip?

00:08:44.080 --> 00:08:45.380
&gt;&gt; Rep. Jackie Speier:
Well, first of all,

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:46.700
I don't think he thought
it was dangerous.

00:08:46.700 --> 00:08:49.590
He presumed that he had
a Congressional shield,

00:08:49.590 --> 00:08:51.660 position:56%
that that would somehow protect him.

00:08:51.660 --> 00:08:56.560 position:56%
Mind you, there were no military
escorts that joined us on that trip.

00:08:56.560 --> 00:09:00.890
He had had a friend whose son had
been involved in the Peoples Temple

00:09:00.890 --> 00:09:04.940
who was mysteriously
killed at a railroad tracks.

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:08.550
We had a number of
constituents in the San Mateo part

00:09:08.550 --> 00:09:11.560
of the district whose young
adult kids got involved

00:09:11.560 --> 00:09:13.200
in the Peoples Temple.

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:15.290
It was a huge church
in San Francisco.

00:09:15.290 --> 00:09:20.540 position:56%
Jim Jones was very politically
active and connected and served both

00:09:20.540 --> 00:09:25.140
on the human rights commission
and then on the housing authority.

00:09:25.140 --> 00:09:26.980
So had it wired there.

00:09:26.980 --> 00:09:32.740
There was a group of family
members that came about concerned

00:09:32.740 --> 00:09:35.400
about loved ones in Jonestown.

00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:38.970
There was a couple who had
been part of the Peoples Temple

00:09:38.970 --> 00:09:42.540
who had their son who
was still in Jonestown

00:09:42.540 --> 00:09:45.140
that they wanted to get out.

00:09:45.140 --> 00:09:49.170
And so this all kind
of came together.

00:09:49.170 --> 00:09:50.570
We have lots of meetings.

00:09:50.570 --> 00:09:54.350
There was a member of the
Peoples Temple who had fled

00:09:54.350 --> 00:09:58.730
through the embassy in
Georgetown, Guyana and come back

00:09:58.730 --> 00:10:03.350
to San Francisco that we
interviewed who talked about all

00:10:03.350 --> 00:10:07.090
of these horrendous activities
going on -- the sexual assault,

00:10:07.090 --> 00:10:11.880
the physical assault, the gun
running, the mind control.

00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:15.980 position:56%
So it was on that basis -- he was
chairing a subcommittee on oversight

00:10:15.980 --> 00:10:19.770
of American citizens abroad -- that
he decided that he was going to do

00:10:19.770 --> 00:10:23.780
like he did before, and that
was to go see firsthand.

00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:27.350
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: So you traveled
to Guyana, and you did get to go

00:10:27.350 --> 00:10:31.320
to Jonestown to see the
Peoples Temple commune.

00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:35.580
You were there for a number
of days and there was unrest.

00:10:35.580 --> 00:10:38.350
And there was even an
assassination attempt

00:10:38.350 --> 00:10:41.730
on Congressman Ryan's
life while you were there.

00:10:41.730 --> 00:10:44.420
And it was decided there
was some people maybe wanted

00:10:44.420 --> 00:10:47.350
to leave Jonestown,
there was defectors.

00:10:47.350 --> 00:10:51.010
And it was decided that you
would vacate, that you would head

00:10:51.010 --> 00:10:53.720
to the airstrip and
there would be planes

00:10:53.720 --> 00:10:56.610
that would be there
to transport you.

00:10:56.610 --> 00:11:00.170
And when you were there, there
was an ambush from people

00:11:00.170 --> 00:11:03.530
from the Peoples Temple,
actually, and they shot

00:11:03.530 --> 00:11:06.280
and killed Congressman Ryan
along with four other people

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:09.830
and severely wounded
you in the process.

00:11:09.830 --> 00:11:14.140
Since it was such a remote
airstrip, you actually stayed there

00:11:14.140 --> 00:11:17.590
for 22 hours without medical
attention or really any help.

00:11:17.590 --> 00:11:20.810
So can you take us back
to that day and talk to us

00:11:20.810 --> 00:11:23.920
about what you were
thinking when that happened

00:11:23.920 --> 00:11:27.570
and how this affected
your future career path

00:11:27.570 --> 00:11:31.770
and your future career
in public service?

00:11:31.770 --> 00:11:36.350
&gt;&gt; Rep. Jackie Speier: So just
to take you back a little bit,

00:11:36.350 --> 00:11:40.140
we were in the commune
for about 20, 24 hours,

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:41.440
maybe a little bit less than that.

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:43.440
We got there, we had a tour.

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:46.700
We started meeting
with family members.

00:11:46.700 --> 00:11:52.690
There was really a script that
they were basically all reading

00:11:52.690 --> 00:11:53.990
in their minds.

00:11:53.990 --> 00:11:57.380 position:56%
And it was, you know, pretty
obvious that there was mind control.

00:11:57.380 --> 00:12:01.930
One of the reporters who was on
the trip, Don Harris from NBC,

00:12:01.930 --> 00:12:05.510
was walking around the perimeter
of the pavilion smoking a cigarette

00:12:05.510 --> 00:12:07.110
and two people slipped him notes.

00:12:07.110 --> 00:12:10.480
That's the first indication we
had that people wanted to leave.

00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:11.790
So we were there overnight.

00:12:11.790 --> 00:12:15.040
The next morning I retrieved
them and their belongings,

00:12:15.040 --> 00:12:17.760
and then word spread and more
and more people wanted to leave.

00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:19.060
And then it became clear

00:12:19.060 --> 00:12:21.210
that we didn't have
enough room in the plane.

00:12:21.210 --> 00:12:23.710
So we were going to
do the first air lift

00:12:23.710 --> 00:12:25.070
and I was going to leave with them.

00:12:25.070 --> 00:12:28.200 position:56%
And Congressman Ryan was going to
stay behind with probably another 40

00:12:28.200 --> 00:12:30.420
or 50 people that wanted to leave.

00:12:30.420 --> 00:12:32.900
There was then the
knifing attempt on him.

00:12:32.900 --> 00:12:34.810
The truck was about to leave.

00:12:34.810 --> 00:12:37.700
We stopped, he got into the
truck, we went to the airstrip.

00:12:37.700 --> 00:12:41.770
Unbeknownst to us, there was a
tractor-trailer following behind us

00:12:41.770 --> 00:12:43.930
with seven gunmen on it.

00:12:43.930 --> 00:12:47.540
I'm coaxing a little Guyanese
child out of the airplane

00:12:47.540 --> 00:12:49.770 position:56%
because he had scampered up into it.

00:12:49.770 --> 00:12:51.610
And we didn't have
enough seats as it was.

00:12:51.610 --> 00:12:53.840
So I was trying to coax him
out so I could put people

00:12:53.840 --> 00:12:56.360
on the plane -- on the two planes.

00:12:56.360 --> 00:12:59.400
And all of a sudden
this noise broke out.

00:12:59.400 --> 00:13:02.060
And at first, I had no
understanding of what it was.

00:13:02.060 --> 00:13:04.080
People ran into the bush.

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:05.750
Congressman Ryan ran
under the plane.

00:13:05.750 --> 00:13:10.870
And so I followed suit and
hid underneath a wheel.

00:13:10.870 --> 00:13:15.670
They came and they had ID'd
who they wanted to kill.

00:13:15.670 --> 00:13:18.980
And so they shot us
at point-blank range.

00:13:18.980 --> 00:13:21.330
Congressman Ryan was shot 45 times.

00:13:21.330 --> 00:13:23.330
And you could be helpful to me

00:13:23.330 --> 00:13:26.050
because I always say I think he's
the only Congressman in the history

00:13:26.050 --> 00:13:28.530
of this country who's been
assassinated in the line of duty.

00:13:28.530 --> 00:13:31.380
But I've never been able
to absolutely confirm it.

00:13:31.380 --> 00:13:32.950
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: That's,
I think, true, actually.

00:13:32.950 --> 00:13:35.810
Because I remember when I worked
at CRS this was an inquiry

00:13:35.810 --> 00:13:37.110
that we had, that we worked on.

00:13:37.110 --> 00:13:38.410
So I actually remember that.

00:13:38.410 --> 00:13:39.710
&gt;&gt; Rep. Jackie Speier: Okay.

00:13:39.710 --> 00:13:41.010
All right.

00:13:41.010 --> 00:13:46.680
And I was lying there, playing
dead and was shot five times.

00:13:46.680 --> 00:13:50.510
The whole right side of
my body was blown up.

00:13:50.510 --> 00:13:53.910
And I looked down and there was
a bone shooting out of my arm

00:13:53.910 --> 00:13:56.660
and my leg was totally blown up.

00:13:56.660 --> 00:13:59.740
And so what happens in a
moment like that is that you --

00:13:59.740 --> 00:14:03.320
you know, you're in
shock, of course.

00:14:03.320 --> 00:14:06.010
But it was almost like
my mind was telling me

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:10.880 position:56%
that half my body was good and half
my body wasn't, and I was just going

00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:17.100
to ignore the half of my body
that, you know, wasn't relevant.

00:14:17.100 --> 00:14:20.880
I was lying there and
literally what do you do

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:22.180
when you think you're dying?

00:14:22.180 --> 00:14:23.480
I mean, I thought,
"My God, this is it.

00:14:23.480 --> 00:14:25.990
I'm 28 years old.

00:14:25.990 --> 00:14:27.290
This is it.

00:14:27.290 --> 00:14:28.590
I'm not going to live to be 85.

00:14:28.590 --> 00:14:30.980
I'm not going to get
married and have 2.5 kids

00:14:30.980 --> 00:14:32.830
and live happily ever after.

00:14:32.830 --> 00:14:34.130
This is it."

00:14:34.130 --> 00:14:37.050
So I was raised as a
good Catholic girl.

00:14:37.050 --> 00:14:41.370
And the first thing I did
was say the act of contrition

00:14:41.370 --> 00:14:43.730
and literally waited for
the lights to go out.

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:49.260 position:56%
And when they didn't, my grandmother
who is in her mid 80's kind

00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:50.560
of flashed in front of me.

00:14:50.560 --> 00:14:53.040
And she was this powerful
matriarch in my family.

00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:55.150
And I said, "I'm not
going to have her live

00:14:55.150 --> 00:14:56.560
through my funeral
if I can avoid it."

00:14:56.560 --> 00:15:01.860
So I kind of dragged my body
to the cargo hold of the plane

00:15:01.860 --> 00:15:05.420
because the engines
were still running.

00:15:05.420 --> 00:15:08.250
And one of the reporters actually
from the <i>Washington Post</i> came

00:15:08.250 --> 00:15:11.460
up behind me and said,
"Hurry up, Jackie."

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:15.170
I can't. So he shoves
me into the cargo hold.

00:15:15.170 --> 00:15:17.340 position:56%
And the plane wasn't going anywhere.

00:15:17.340 --> 00:15:20.320
There were bullet holes through
the engine and one of the wheels.

00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:22.870
And eventually they took
me out of the plane,

00:15:22.870 --> 00:15:25.320
put me on the side of the airstrip.

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:28.650
Unfortunately, it was
on an ant hill.

00:15:28.650 --> 00:15:31.830
But you don't sweat the small
stuff when you're dying.

00:15:31.830 --> 00:15:40.600
So one of the reporters had a tape
recorder nearby, and I asked him

00:15:40.600 --> 00:15:42.980
if I could leave a
message for my parents.

00:15:42.980 --> 00:15:50.030
And so I tape recorded a message to
my parents and kind of a last will.

00:15:50.030 --> 00:15:54.500
And then was on that airstrip for
22 hours without medical attention.

00:15:54.500 --> 00:15:56.670
There was a tent nearby,
so they put me in the tent.

00:15:56.670 --> 00:16:03.440
And through the night the producer
for the NBC affiliate would come

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:09.290
over to the tent because they were
now at a bar in Matthew's Ridge.

00:16:09.290 --> 00:16:13.260
He would bring a bottle of rum --

00:16:13.260 --> 00:16:15.450
Guyanese rum -- for
me to take swigs of.

00:16:15.450 --> 00:16:18.290
And it was very potent,
Guyanese rum.

00:16:18.290 --> 00:16:21.070
So that's how I got
through the night.

00:16:21.070 --> 00:16:27.050
But it was those moments
that I decided if I survived,

00:16:27.050 --> 00:16:28.810
I would never take a
never day for granted,

00:16:28.810 --> 00:16:32.270
and that I would live every
day as fully as possible,

00:16:32.270 --> 00:16:35.060
and that I would commit
my life to public service.

00:16:35.060 --> 00:16:40.380
And so that was kind of one
of those defining moments.

00:16:40.380 --> 00:16:44.850
And it really provided
me an extraordinary gift

00:16:44.850 --> 00:16:47.180
because at a very young
age I learned

00:16:47.180 --> 00:16:50.540
that there were no tomorrows --
no tomorrows were guaranteed --

00:16:50.540 --> 00:16:53.260
and how precious every moment was.

00:16:53.260 --> 00:16:58.750
And once you've almost died,
you're not afraid nearly as much

00:16:58.750 --> 00:17:04.100
to do things that others
might see as a little risky.

00:17:04.100 --> 00:17:06.650
