00:18:33.560 --> 00:18:36.310
<i>This is Not the Life I
Ordered</i> with three other women.

00:18:36.310 --> 00:18:39.780
Can you tell us the story of this
book, why did you write this book

00:18:39.780 --> 00:18:43.210
and how did you come to write
it with three of your friends?

00:18:43.210 --> 00:18:47.220
&gt;&gt; Rep. Jackie Speier: So this
book was five years in the making.

00:18:47.220 --> 00:18:51.110
A group of friends and I would
get together once a month

00:18:51.110 --> 00:18:53.690
to help each other,
to support each other.

00:18:53.690 --> 00:18:56.650
We'd all gone through
traumatic experiences.

00:18:56.650 --> 00:19:01.000
I had lost my husband in
an automobile accident

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:03.700
when I was pregnant with
our second child 14 years

00:19:03.700 --> 00:19:05.000
after Guyana happened.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.560
And I'd always thought everyone
gets their fair share of grief,

00:19:07.560 --> 00:19:11.220
but then that happened and it
was incredibly devastating.

00:19:11.220 --> 00:19:14.580
So we would get together
and have lunch.

00:19:14.580 --> 00:19:17.540
And the rationale for getting
together every month was

00:19:17.540 --> 00:19:19.210
that we were going to write a book.

00:19:19.210 --> 00:19:23.450
We never put pen to paper
for the first four years

00:19:23.450 --> 00:19:26.360
and then eventually
did and wrote the book.

00:19:26.360 --> 00:19:32.030
And it became a -- and we told
stories, not just our own but those

00:19:32.030 --> 00:19:35.100
of other women who had gone
through very difficult times.

00:19:35.100 --> 00:19:38.570
And it became kind of a how-to
book of how do you get through it?

00:19:38.570 --> 00:19:40.710
What are the tips?

00:19:40.710 --> 00:19:44.220
You know, creating a
gratitude journal was one

00:19:44.220 --> 00:19:46.270
of the tips that we suggested.

00:19:46.270 --> 00:19:50.580
And the first day it may be
only that your dog didn't pee

00:19:50.580 --> 00:19:54.650
in the carpet, but, you know, the
next day it may be something else.

00:19:54.650 --> 00:20:00.260
And we also suggested that what
we had created was really key

00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:02.020
to our being able to survive.

00:20:02.020 --> 00:20:04.190
And that was what we
called kitchen table.

00:20:04.190 --> 00:20:06.630
So getting a group
of people together

00:20:06.630 --> 00:20:09.110
as a kitchen table
that would support you.

00:20:09.110 --> 00:20:12.630
And that's the only reason it
exists, is just to be together.

00:20:12.630 --> 00:20:17.260
And I've noticed in my life that I
have a number of groups like that.

00:20:17.260 --> 00:20:23.300
I have -- we created a married
widows club after I lost my husband

00:20:23.300 --> 00:20:25.050
and then a friend lost her husband.

00:20:25.050 --> 00:20:27.030
And she's actually one of
the co-authors of the book.

00:20:27.030 --> 00:20:30.900
And so over the years
there's been about 14 of us.

00:20:30.900 --> 00:20:32.800
No one wants to join
this particular club.

00:20:32.800 --> 00:20:36.300
But it has been a great
source of support.

00:20:36.300 --> 00:20:38.450 position:56%
And then I have my yoga girlfriends.

00:20:38.450 --> 00:20:40.460
And for the longest time
