00:46:32.400 --> 00:46:34.440
up a hill and we never think
we're going to get it up.

00:46:34.440 --> 00:46:38.090
I mean, that's a great example with
sexual assault in the military.

00:46:38.090 --> 00:46:40.290
I mean, yes, it should be taken
out of the chain of command.

00:46:40.290 --> 00:46:42.940 position:56%
That's what my legislation would do.

00:46:42.940 --> 00:46:46.370
But we have gotten a number
of significant improvements

00:46:46.370 --> 00:46:49.900
to the Uniform Code of Military
Justice in the last five years

00:46:49.900 --> 00:46:52.740
by some of the amendments
that we have gotten

00:46:52.740 --> 00:46:56.880
into the law that's
improved the status of those

00:46:56.880 --> 00:46:58.800
who are sexually assaulted.

00:46:58.800 --> 00:47:01.650
I continue to be concerned
about whistleblowers

00:47:01.650 --> 00:47:04.290
and the retaliation
that they endure.

00:47:04.290 --> 00:47:08.450 position:56%
And we're dealing with that kind of
issue in the intelligence committee.

00:47:08.450 --> 00:47:13.190
So those are all issues that I
feel very strongly about and intend

00:47:13.190 --> 00:47:15.220
to be here to see them through.

00:47:15.220 --> 00:47:17.930
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: We have
one question over here.

00:47:17.930 --> 00:47:19.520
Oh no, no, no.

00:47:19.520 --> 00:47:23.730
You over here and then over here.

00:47:23.730 --> 00:47:25.280
&gt;&gt; Hi. I want to thank
you for your work

00:47:25.280 --> 00:47:27.280
on sexual assault in the military.

00:47:27.280 --> 00:47:29.120
And I'm wondering if you
had done any studies --

00:47:29.120 --> 00:47:32.350
and this is on behalf
on a cousin of mine --

00:47:32.350 --> 00:47:35.180
on the link between sexual
assault in the military

00:47:35.180 --> 00:47:39.830
and our epidemic of
military suicides?

00:47:39.830 --> 00:47:42.760
&gt;&gt; Rep. Jackie Speier: I
have not done any studies,

00:47:42.760 --> 00:47:47.710
but I know that there
is some link to that.

00:47:47.710 --> 00:47:52.960
Because you can just see the
downward spiral that takes place.

00:47:52.960 --> 00:47:56.900
What I was astonished by as
I got to meet more and more

00:47:56.900 --> 00:48:02.320
of these survivors is
particularly the women were legacy.

00:48:02.320 --> 00:48:06.180 position:56%
I mean, their fathers and
grandfathers and uncles had all been

00:48:06.180 --> 00:48:10.190
in the military and this
was a family commitment.

00:48:10.190 --> 00:48:14.390
And because it's an all volunteer
military now, these are people

00:48:14.390 --> 00:48:17.300
who join because they want
to make a career of it.

00:48:17.300 --> 00:48:20.940
And because they're sexually
assaulted and they report it,

00:48:20.940 --> 00:48:24.930
they basically lose their jobs.

00:48:24.930 --> 00:48:28.170
They're labeled with
personality disorder.

00:48:28.170 --> 00:48:36.310
Imagine a DD214 that you then
take to a future employer

00:48:36.310 --> 00:48:38.180
and it says you have a
personality disorder.

00:48:38.180 --> 00:48:40.760 position:56%
I mean, that's what they were doing.

00:48:40.760 --> 00:48:44.150
So you could see how their
lives could easily unravel

00:48:44.150 --> 00:48:53.620 position:56%
and that suicide would be, you know,
their alternative to continuing

00:48:53.620 --> 00:48:56.510
to live in a state
that was unacceptable.

00:48:56.510 --> 00:49:03.510
But I have not actually done any
kind of study on that [inaudible].

00:49:03.510 --> 00:49:16.590
[ Inaudible ]

00:49:16.590 --> 00:49:19.690
&gt;&gt; Rep. Jackie Speier: Well,
my schedule is not typical.

00:49:19.690 --> 00:49:23.470
I don't know what typical is.

00:49:23.470 --> 00:49:28.960
You know, the very first campaign I
ran for after I lost for Congress,

00:49:28.960 --> 00:49:31.700
I was running for the board
of supervisors and I was told

00:49:31.700 --> 00:49:35.340
"Make this call, you're going
to get a $250 contribution."

00:49:35.340 --> 00:49:37.660
And I hemmed and hawed
and then I made the call

00:49:37.660 --> 00:49:39.560
and I got $100 contribution.

00:49:39.560 --> 00:49:44.100
So I've never been good at this.

00:49:44.100 --> 00:49:47.750
So I'm not the type that
will get on the phone

00:49:47.750 --> 00:49:50.870
and just raise money
for the most part.

00:49:50.870 --> 00:49:53.390
I will do an event in my district.

00:49:53.390 --> 00:49:55.980
And people will come to the event.

00:49:55.980 --> 00:50:00.670
But I would say in terms
of doing events back here,

00:50:00.670 --> 00:50:05.160
maybe four hours a month?

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:11.720
Not what I would say is typical.

00:50:13.620 --> 00:50:14.920
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Other questions?

00:50:14.920 --> 00:50:16.620
Yes, right here [inaudible].

00:50:16.620 --> 00:50:17.920
&gt;&gt; Last question.

00:50:17.920 --> 00:50:20.510
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan:
Last question, okay.

00:50:20.510 --> 00:51:19.410
[ Inaudible ]

00:51:19.410 --> 00:51:21.500
&gt;&gt; Rep. Jackie Speier:
That's a very good question.

00:51:21.500 --> 00:51:24.200 position:56%
When we were about to make the trip,

00:51:24.200 --> 00:51:26.400
the State Department kept
telling us, "You know,

00:51:26.400 --> 00:51:32.040
we can't force Jim
Jones to meet with you.

00:51:32.040 --> 00:51:34.630
You have to get an
invitation on your own.

00:51:34.630 --> 00:51:36.970
We have visited the commune.

00:51:36.970 --> 00:51:38.980
They seem very happy.

00:51:38.980 --> 00:51:44.020
Everyone seems to be
glad to be there."

00:51:44.020 --> 00:51:46.760
Meanwhile, you know, we've already
had some defectors who have come

00:51:46.760 --> 00:51:49.730
through the councilor office.

00:51:49.730 --> 00:51:55.930
We had a briefing in the
embassy in Georgetown a day

00:51:55.930 --> 00:51:58.850
or two before we actually
went to Jonestown.

00:51:58.850 --> 00:52:01.720
And they provided us
with a slide show.

00:52:01.720 --> 00:52:04.200
Now mind you, the slide
show had a picture

00:52:04.200 --> 00:52:09.810
of our two councilor officers
with Jim Jones arm in arm.

00:52:09.810 --> 00:52:12.980
What kind of message
was that sending?

00:52:12.980 --> 00:52:24.170 position:56%
So I was pretty critical of State in
terms of their lack of recognition

00:52:24.170 --> 00:52:27.850
that they had a responsibility
to follow up on so many

00:52:27.850 --> 00:52:31.370
of these inquiries that had been
made about people being held there

00:52:31.370 --> 00:52:37.010
against their will, Social Security
checks being improperly handled.

00:52:37.010 --> 00:52:43.920
And I believe that the political
trumped the councilor function

00:52:43.920 --> 00:52:45.220
in that regard.

00:52:45.220 --> 00:52:47.820
And bauxite was a very
important component.

00:52:47.820 --> 00:52:52.580
We were importing a lot of
bauxite from Guyana at the time.

00:52:52.580 --> 00:52:57.230
And I think those interests trumped
the interests of Americans citizen

00:52:57.230 --> 00:53:00.710
that were being held
there against their will.

00:53:01.830 --> 00:53:03.220
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Please
join me in thanking --

00:53:03.220 --> 00:53:04.590
&gt;&gt; Rep. Jackie Speier:
I have one more comment.

00:53:04.590 --> 00:53:05.890
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Sorry.

00:53:05.890 --> 00:53:08.890
I should have had known.

00:53:08.890 --> 00:53:10.650
Right? I should have learned.

00:53:10.650 --> 00:53:14.630 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Rep. Jackie Speier: I just want
to leave you with you've got a sense

00:53:14.630 --> 00:53:24.520
of how my life has meandered,
and I didn't touch on the loss

00:53:24.520 --> 00:53:28.780
of my husband when I was
pregnant with our second child.

00:53:28.780 --> 00:53:33.510
But it was another traumatic
experience in my life.

00:53:33.510 --> 00:53:35.310
But I've learned something
that's very important.

00:53:35.310 --> 00:53:37.320
And the quotation I want
to share with you is one

00:53:37.320 --> 00:53:41.750
that I hope you will keep in mind.

00:53:41.750 --> 00:53:45.500
"Life should not be a journey
with the intention of arriving

00:53:45.500 --> 00:53:50.350
in a well-preserved body
at the end of your life,

00:53:50.350 --> 00:53:54.940
but rather you should be totally
worn out, totally used up --

00:53:54.940 --> 00:53:57.490
martini in one hand,
chocolate in the other,

00:53:57.490 --> 00:53:59.210
screaming, 'Woo hoo, what a ride.'"

00:53:59.210 --> 00:54:00.510
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: All right.

00:54:00.510 --> 00:54:03.510
Thank you so much.

